T1  - Adaptive Treatment Assignment in Experiments for Policy Choice
AU  - Kasy, Maximilian
AU  - Sautmann, Anja
Y1  - 2021/01/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA17527
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 113
EP  - 132
VL  - 89
IS  - 1
KW  - Experimental design
KW  - field experiments
KW  - optimal policy
KW  - multi-armed bandits
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA17527
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Standard experimental designs are geared toward point estimation and hypothesis testing, while bandit algorithms are geared toward in-sample outcomes. Here, we instead consider treatment assignment in an experiment with several waves for choosing the best among a set of possible policies (treatments) at the end of the experiment. We propose a computationally tractable assignment algorithm that we call ?exploration sampling,? where assignment probabilities in each wave are an increasing concave function of the posterior probabilities that each treatment is optimal. We prove an asymptotic optimality result for this algorithm and demonstrate improvements in welfare in calibrated simulations over both non-adaptive designs and bandit algorithms. An application to selecting between six different recruitment strategies for an agricultural extension service in India demonstrates practical feasibility.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Policy Learning With Observational Data
AU  - Athey, Susan
AU  - Wager, Stefan
Y1  - 2021/01/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA15732
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 133
EP  - 161
VL  - 89
IS  - 1
KW  - Double robustness
KW  - empirical welfare maximization
KW  - minimax regret
KW  - semiparametric efficiency
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA15732
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In many areas, practitioners seek to use observational data to learn a treatment assignment policy that satisfies application-specific constraints, such as budget, fairness, simplicity, or other functional form constraints. For example, policies may be restricted to take the form of decision trees based on a limited set of easily observable individual characteristics. We propose a new approach to this problem motivated by the theory of semiparametrically efficient estimation. Our method can be used to optimize either binary treatments or infinitesimal nudges to continuous treatments, and can leverage observational data where causal effects are identified using a variety of strategies, including selection on observables and instrumental variables. Given a doubly robust estimator of the causal effect of assigning everyone to treatment, we develop an algorithm for choosing whom to treat, and establish strong guarantees for the asymptotic utilitarian regret of the resulting policy.
ER  - 

